description: From Middle English extinct, from Latin extīnctus, the past participle of extinguere (“to put out, destroy, abolish, extinguish”), corresponding to ex- + stinguere (“to quench”). Replaced native Middle English aqueint, aquenched (“extinguished, extinct”).

entries.meaning: (dated) Extinguished, no longer alight (of fire, candles etc.)
examples: Poor Edward's cigarillo was already extinct.
The title became extinct when the last baron died.
Luckily, such ideas about race are extinct in current sociological theory.

entries.meaning: (of a group of organisms, as a species) No longer in existence; having died out.
examples: The dinosaurs have been extinct for millions of years.
Most of the volcanos on this island are now extinct.
They found the sites of extinct geysers.

description: From Middle English extincten, from the adjective (see above).

verbs.description: extinct (third-person singular simple present extincts, present participle extincting, simple past and past participle extincted)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To make extinct; to extinguish or annihilate.
